{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/kubernetes/2024-1study/167serviceaccounts/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Service Accounts","date":"May 23, 2024"},"html":"<h1>Service Accounts</h1>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 40%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"types\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/5a190/call.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/772e8/call.png 200w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/e17e5/call.png 400w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/5a190/call.png 800w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/c1b63/call.png 1200w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/29007/call.png 1600w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/05244/call.png 1752w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>There are two types of accounts in Kubernetes: User Accounts and Service Accounts. User accounts are for humans, while Service Accounts are for applications running in the cluster.</p>\n<p>For example, a monitoring application like Prometheus or a logging application like Fluentd would use a Service Account to interact with the Kubernetes API for performance monitoring or log collection.</p>\n<p>An automated tool like Jenkins would also use a Service Account to deploy applications on the cluster.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Example</h3>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 36.50000000000001%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"ex\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/b6f100ec44b91afb59668744a00e4d8c/5a190/ex.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/b6f100ec44b91afb59668744a00e4d8c/772e8/ex.png 200w,\n/static/b6f100ec44b91afb59668744a00e4d8c/e17e5/ex.png 400w,\n/static/b6f100ec44b91afb59668744a00e4d8c/5a190/ex.png 800w,\n/static/b6f100ec44b91afb59668744a00e4d8c/c1b63/ex.png 1200w,\n/static/b6f100ec44b91afb59668744a00e4d8c/29007/ex.png 1600w,\n/static/b6f100ec44b91afb59668744a00e4d8c/fb937/ex.png 1820w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Let's view an example. Here is a simple Kube Dashboard implemented in python that shows the current pods by calling the kube API.</p>\n<p>In order for the application to query the kube API, it needs to be authenticated. To do so, it uses a Service Account.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 76.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"cmd\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/3c5e4835cc00e3fe1a25e19a976fb3c3/5a190/cmds.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/3c5e4835cc00e3fe1a25e19a976fb3c3/772e8/cmds.png 200w,\n/static/3c5e4835cc00e3fe1a25e19a976fb3c3/e17e5/cmds.png 400w,\n/static/3c5e4835cc00e3fe1a25e19a976fb3c3/5a190/cmds.png 800w,\n/static/3c5e4835cc00e3fe1a25e19a976fb3c3/c6ff8/cmds.png 1088w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>To create a Service Account, we call <code>kubectl create serviceaccount &#x3C;name></code>. This creates a Service Account in the default namespace.</p>\n<p>To view a list of Service Accounts, we call <code>kubectl get serviceaccounts</code>.</p>\n<p>When a Service Account is created, it automatically creates a token, which is what must be used by an external object to authenticate with the kube API.</p>\n<p>To view the token, we call <code>kubectl describe secret &#x3C;secret-name></code></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 51.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"secret\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/e2c87856076e227de2f591da109a769c/5a190/secret.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/e2c87856076e227de2f591da109a769c/772e8/secret.png 200w,\n/static/e2c87856076e227de2f591da109a769c/e17e5/secret.png 400w,\n/static/e2c87856076e227de2f591da109a769c/5a190/secret.png 800w,\n/static/e2c87856076e227de2f591da109a769c/c1b63/secret.png 1200w,\n/static/e2c87856076e227de2f591da109a769c/29007/secret.png 1600w,\n/static/e2c87856076e227de2f591da109a769c/460fa/secret.png 1910w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span>\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 40%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"call\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/5a190/call.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/772e8/call.png 200w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/e17e5/call.png 400w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/5a190/call.png 800w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/c1b63/call.png 1200w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/29007/call.png 1600w,\n/static/f67e2771b64d68861198a2cf040d6d0e/05244/call.png 1752w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>As such we can use the token to make a call to the kube API.</p>\n<h2>What if the 3rd party application is hosted within the Kube Cluster?</h2>\n<p>If instead of an external application, if the application is hosted within the kube cluster itself, the authentication can be simply by automatically mounting the Service Account token as a volume inside the pod.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 31.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"within\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/202b592cba4cdfdffae6fbe431fabdc5/5a190/withinpod.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/202b592cba4cdfdffae6fbe431fabdc5/772e8/withinpod.png 200w,\n/static/202b592cba4cdfdffae6fbe431fabdc5/e17e5/withinpod.png 400w,\n/static/202b592cba4cdfdffae6fbe431fabdc5/5a190/withinpod.png 800w,\n/static/202b592cba4cdfdffae6fbe431fabdc5/c1b63/withinpod.png 1200w,\n/static/202b592cba4cdfdffae6fbe431fabdc5/29007/withinpod.png 1600w,\n/static/202b592cba4cdfdffae6fbe431fabdc5/69d6b/withinpod.png 1912w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>For every namespace in Kubernetes, there is a default Service Account. Whenever a pod is created, the default service account and its token are automatically mounted to that pod as a volume mount.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 54%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"def\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/97ddbd8213cda9439a5f35c4bc2adcd2/5a190/def.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/97ddbd8213cda9439a5f35c4bc2adcd2/772e8/def.png 200w,\n/static/97ddbd8213cda9439a5f35c4bc2adcd2/e17e5/def.png 400w,\n/static/97ddbd8213cda9439a5f35c4bc2adcd2/5a190/def.png 800w,\n/static/97ddbd8213cda9439a5f35c4bc2adcd2/c1b63/def.png 1200w,\n/static/97ddbd8213cda9439a5f35c4bc2adcd2/29007/def.png 1600w,\n/static/97ddbd8213cda9439a5f35c4bc2adcd2/69d6b/def.png 1912w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 50.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"token\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/3af4a52af17391c3c083b626b553f063/5a190/token.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/3af4a52af17391c3c083b626b553f063/772e8/token.png 200w,\n/static/3af4a52af17391c3c083b626b553f063/e17e5/token.png 400w,\n/static/3af4a52af17391c3c083b626b553f063/5a190/token.png 800w,\n/static/3af4a52af17391c3c083b626b553f063/c1b63/token.png 1200w,\n/static/3af4a52af17391c3c083b626b553f063/29007/token.png 1600w,\n/static/3af4a52af17391c3c083b626b553f063/7e318/token.png 1892w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span>\nWe can see the the actual token is saved within 'token'.</p>\n<p>However, the default service account is very restricted and only has basic permissions to run kube api queries. If you want to give more permissions, you can create a custom service account and modify the pod definition file to include a service accoutn field. However, we cannot edit the service account field of an existing pod. In such case, we need to delete the pod and recreate it.</p>\n<p>However, in the case of a deployment, any changes to the pod definition file will automatically trigger a rollout for the deployment.</p>\n<p>You may choose not to automatically mount a service account by setting automountServiceAccountToken to false in the pod definition file.</p>\n<h1>Service Account Updates V1.22</h1>\n<p>Previously, tokens didn't have an expiration date as shown below.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 49%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"jwt\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/a29c5b93dde2bab4986efd50cfb5168e/5a190/jwt.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/a29c5b93dde2bab4986efd50cfb5168e/772e8/jwt.png 200w,\n/static/a29c5b93dde2bab4986efd50cfb5168e/e17e5/jwt.png 400w,\n/static/a29c5b93dde2bab4986efd50cfb5168e/5a190/jwt.png 800w,\n/static/a29c5b93dde2bab4986efd50cfb5168e/c1b63/jwt.png 1200w,\n/static/a29c5b93dde2bab4986efd50cfb5168e/29007/jwt.png 1600w,\n/static/a29c5b93dde2bab4986efd50cfb5168e/169e3/jwt.png 1682w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>However, this causes problems since the current jwt isn't audience bound or time bound. As such, the Kubernetes 1.22 has the following comments regarding security and scalability issues.\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 46%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"1.22\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/2b4fbccbd2ca39d5035f9933d8f02b22/5a190/jwt1-22.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/2b4fbccbd2ca39d5035f9933d8f02b22/772e8/jwt1-22.png 200w,\n/static/2b4fbccbd2ca39d5035f9933d8f02b22/e17e5/jwt1-22.png 400w,\n/static/2b4fbccbd2ca39d5035f9933d8f02b22/5a190/jwt1-22.png 800w,\n/static/2b4fbccbd2ca39d5035f9933d8f02b22/c1b63/jwt1-22.png 1200w,\n/static/2b4fbccbd2ca39d5035f9933d8f02b22/29007/jwt1-22.png 1600w,\n/static/2b4fbccbd2ca39d5035f9933d8f02b22/460fa/jwt1-22.png 1910w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>This would mean that as long as the service account exists, the jwt token would be valid. This is a security risk since the token could be used by an attacker to gain access to the kube API.</p>\n<p>As such, in version 1.22, the <strong>token request API</strong> was introduced which makes tokens more scalable and secure via an API, making them audience bound, time bound, and object bound.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 49.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"token122\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/078124c8ca3cb79125dfbd745cacf6da/5a190/token122.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/078124c8ca3cb79125dfbd745cacf6da/772e8/token122.png 200w,\n/static/078124c8ca3cb79125dfbd745cacf6da/e17e5/token122.png 400w,\n/static/078124c8ca3cb79125dfbd745cacf6da/5a190/token122.png 800w,\n/static/078124c8ca3cb79125dfbd745cacf6da/c1b63/token122.png 1200w,\n/static/078124c8ca3cb79125dfbd745cacf6da/0d390/token122.png 1472w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Therefore, since version 1.22, when a pod is newly created it no longer relies on the service account but rather on the token request API to get a timed token.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 51%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"timed\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/c6e5672ac4619ed6dd09b7e715db370f/5a190/timedtoken.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/c6e5672ac4619ed6dd09b7e715db370f/772e8/timedtoken.png 200w,\n/static/c6e5672ac4619ed6dd09b7e715db370f/e17e5/timedtoken.png 400w,\n/static/c6e5672ac4619ed6dd09b7e715db370f/5a190/timedtoken.png 800w,\n/static/c6e5672ac4619ed6dd09b7e715db370f/c1b63/timedtoken.png 1200w,\n/static/c6e5672ac4619ed6dd09b7e715db370f/29007/timedtoken.png 1600w,\n/static/c6e5672ac4619ed6dd09b7e715db370f/5c263/timedtoken.png 1636w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<h1>Service Account Updates V1.24</h1>\n<p>Enhancement regarding the reduction of secret-based service account tokens. Previously, when a service account was created it would automatically create a secret with a token.</p>\n<p>With version 1.24, it would no longer create a secret by default. Therefore, you must run the command <code>kubectl create token &#x3C;name></code> to create a secret or token access secret.</p>\n<p>This token will have an expiry date defined, and if the time limit wasn't specified then it will usually be one hour.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 58.50000000000001%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"1.24\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/afda0a243c22a72322d85b239df66de7/5a190/jwt1-24.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/afda0a243c22a72322d85b239df66de7/772e8/jwt1-24.png 200w,\n/static/afda0a243c22a72322d85b239df66de7/e17e5/jwt1-24.png 400w,\n/static/afda0a243c22a72322d85b239df66de7/5a190/jwt1-24.png 800w,\n/static/afda0a243c22a72322d85b239df66de7/c1b63/jwt1-24.png 1200w,\n/static/afda0a243c22a72322d85b239df66de7/29007/jwt1-24.png 1600w,\n/static/afda0a243c22a72322d85b239df66de7/701e9/jwt1-24.png 1780w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>In versions post 1.24, if we still want to create a secret with a nonexpiring token, we can use the type kubernetes.io/service-account-token.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 42.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"io\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/e1469d3b5ad5a64a3c4fc6ab88fd5e7e/5a190/post1-24.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/e1469d3b5ad5a64a3c4fc6ab88fd5e7e/772e8/post1-24.png 200w,\n/static/e1469d3b5ad5a64a3c4fc6ab88fd5e7e/e17e5/post1-24.png 400w,\n/static/e1469d3b5ad5a64a3c4fc6ab88fd5e7e/5a190/post1-24.png 800w,\n/static/e1469d3b5ad5a64a3c4fc6ab88fd5e7e/c1b63/post1-24.png 1200w,\n/static/e1469d3b5ad5a64a3c4fc6ab88fd5e7e/29007/post1-24.png 1600w,\n/static/e1469d3b5ad5a64a3c4fc6ab88fd5e7e/a8979/post1-24.png 1828w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>However, this should only be done when creating tokens using the API can't be done.</p>"}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/kubernetes/2024-1study/167serviceaccounts/"}},"staticQueryHashes":[],"slicesMap":{}}